         <abstract>
            <p>The author challenges the widely held notion that captive finance companies increase corporate debt capacity. He concludes instead that, by lenders' own tests, a reduction in aggregate borrowing power should follow from a decision to set up a credit subsidiary. The analysis can be extended to the general case of segmental debt financing.</p>
         </abstract>
